                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>On May 9, 1954, <persName corresp="#p_BBGCH1">Brigadier General Charles H.
                        Bonesteel III</persName>, Defense Member on the Planning Board of the
                    National Security Council, addressed a memorandum to <persName corresp="#p_WCE1"
                        >Charles E. Wilson</persName>, the Secretary of Defense, titled “Future U.S.
                    Action Regarding Indo-China.” For text, see <hi rend="italic">United
                        States–Vietnam Relations, 1945–1967</hi>, Book 9, page 442. <pb facs="0140"
                        n="1522" xml:id="pg_1522"/> The General prepared a second memorandum, titled
                    “A Concept for Action with Regard to Indochina,” which was submitted to the
                    Planning Board on May 13. For text, see <hi rend="italic">United States–Vietnam
                        Relations, 1945–1967</hi>, Book 9, pages 460–461. A copy in the <persName
                        corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> Library bears the handwritten
                    notation “<persName corresp="#p_BBGCH1">Bonesteel</persName> May 11, 1954.”
                        (<persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> Library, White House
                    Office, “Project ‘Clean Up’”)</p>
            </div>
